<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Shall's original quote:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>there is a group in comm1 and a group in comm2 .. rhag1 pops.. is this automatically comm1's mob, just because they are on the same floor? Even though they need to MOVE to it.. NO it's whoever it is that gets to the mobs room first.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
He's saying that there are 2 groups both camping different camps (comm 1 and comm 2) close to each other and Rhag 1 pops which is in neither of these two camps. Even though comm 1's camp is on the same (bottom) floor and somewhat closer to Rhag 1, it gives them no more claim to Rhag 1 than the comm 2 group who is on the second floor above them. What settles who gets the mob (Rhag 1 in this example) is which group gets to the room first and engages the mob. Whoever kills the mob first (should they have the force to continue the cycle) has the claim to the other mobs in the cycle they started, by killing the trigger mob. If the first group to engage was to wipe, they would lose their claim to the camp/mob. Should the second group also wipe, same deal. If they both wipe, I suppose it would be back to square one and whoever is ready and engages first again would get the first shot.<br>
